      <abstract>
        <p>Brief review by Janet Maslin of film Inventing the Abbotts, which has been released to home video market (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Inventing the Abbotts  Fox. $100.71. Laser disk, $39.98. 110 minutes. Closed captioned. R.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>Inventing the Abbotts  Fox. $100.71. Laser disk, $39.98. 110 minutes. Closed captioned. R.</p>
        <p>Pat O'Connor's film prettily pads out Sue Miller's strongly drawn 30-page short story about three Midwestern girls of the late 50's and the boys they generally hold sway over. Jennifer Connelly is the promiscuous Abbott sister and Joanna Going the ladylike Abbott who marries unhappily into prim conventionality. On a pedestal is Liv Tyler as the youngest Abbott, who determines not to repeat her sisters' mistakes. As the Holt brothers, Joaquin Phoenix and Billy Crudup fit in as required in a film that has the look down pat but ''lacks defining moments and strong passions'' (Maslin).</p>
      </block>
